<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">ISO 3166-1 alpha-2</h1>
<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
<div id="contentSub"></div>
<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
Jump to: <a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, <a href="#p-search">search</a>
</div>
<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:402px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg/400px-Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg.png" width="400" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg/600px-Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg/800px-Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="700" data-file-height="512" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Europe_ISO_3166-1.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A map of Europe, with ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes in place of the names of countries and other territories</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>ISO 3166-1 alpha-2</b> <a href="/wiki/Code" title="Code">codes</a> are two-letter <a href="/wiki/Country_code" title="Country code">country codes</a> defined in <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-1" title="ISO 3166-1">ISO 3166-1</a>, part of the <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166" title="ISO 3166">ISO 3166</a> <a href="/wiki/Standardization" title="Standardization">standard</a> published by the <a href="/wiki/International_Organization_for_Standardization" title="International Organization for Standardization">International Organization for Standardization</a> (ISO), to represent <a href="/wiki/Country" title="Country">countries</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dependent_territory" title="Dependent territory">dependent territories</a>, and special areas of geographical interest. They are the most widely used of the country codes published by ISO (the others being <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-3" title="ISO 3166-1 alpha-3">alpha-3</a> and <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-1_numeric" title="ISO 3166-1 numeric">numeric</a>), and are used most prominently for the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Country_code_top-level_domain" title="Country code top-level domain">country code top-level domains</a> (with a few exceptions).<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> They were first included as part of the ISO 3166 standard in its first edition in 1974.</p>
<p></p>

<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Uses_and_applications">Uses and applications</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Uses and applications">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes are used in different environments and are also part of other standards. In some cases they are not perfectly implemented.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Perfect_implementations">Perfect implementations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Perfect implementations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes are used in the following standards:</p>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr>
<th>Short name</th>
<th>Long name</th>
<th>Comment</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-2" title="ISO 3166-2">ISO 3166-2</a></td>
<td>Country subdivision code<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup></td>
<td></td>
</tr>

<td></td>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Imperfect_implementations">Imperfect implementations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Imperfect implementations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Starting in 1985, ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes have been used in the <a href="/wiki/Domain_Name_System" title="Domain Name System">Domain Name System</a> as <a href="/wiki/Country_code_top-level_domain" title="Country code top-level domain">country code top-level domains</a> (ccTLDs). The <a href="/wiki/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority" title="Internet Assigned Numbers Authority">Internet Assigned Numbers Authority</a> currently assigns the ccTLDs mostly following the alpha-2 codes, but with a few exceptions.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> For example, the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, whose alpha-2 code is <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GB</span>, uses <a href="/wiki/.uk" title=".uk">.uk</a> instead of <a href="/wiki/.gb" title=".gb">.gb</a> as its ccTLD, as <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">UK</span> is currently <a href="#Exceptional_reservations">exceptionally reserved</a> in ISO 3166-1 on the request of the United Kingdom.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">WIPO</a> coding standard ST.3 is based on ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes, but includes a number of additional codes for international <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property_organization" title="Intellectual property organization">intellectual property organizations</a>, which are currently <a href="#Codes_currently_agreed_not_to_use">reserved and not used at the present stage</a> in ISO 3166-1.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup></p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/European_Commission" title="European Commission">European Commission</a> generally uses ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes with two exceptions: <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EL</span> (not <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GR</span>) is used to represent <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greece</a>, and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">UK</span> (not <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GB</span>) is used to represent the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> This notwithstanding, the <i>Official Journal of the European Communities</i> specified that <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GR</span> and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GB</span> be used to represent Greece and United Kingdom respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> For <a href="/wiki/Value_added_tax" class="mw-redirect" title="Value added tax">VAT</a> administration purposes, the <a href="/wiki/European_Commission" title="European Commission">European Commission</a> uses <a href="/wiki/VAT_identification_number#European_Union_VAT_identification_numbers" title="VAT identification number"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EL</span> and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GB</span> for Greece and the United Kingdom respectively.</a></p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> uses a combination of ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 and <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-3" title="ISO 3166-1 alpha-3">alpha-3</a> codes, along with codes that pre-date the creation of ISO 3166, for <a href="/wiki/List_of_international_vehicle_registration_codes" title="List of international vehicle registration codes">international vehicle registration codes</a>, which are codes used to identify the issuing country of a vehicle registration plate; some of these codes are currently <a href="#Indeterminate_reservations">indeterminately reserved</a> in ISO 3166-1.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup></p>
<p><a href="/wiki/IETF_language_tag" title="IETF language tag">IETF language tags</a> (conforming to the BCP 47 standard track and maintained in an <a href="/wiki/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority" title="Internet Assigned Numbers Authority">IANA</a> registry) are also partially derived from ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes (for the region subtags). The full list of ISO 3166-1 codes assigned to countries and territories are usable as region subtags. Also, the "exceptionally reserved" alpha-2 codes defined in ISO 3166-1 (with the exception of <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">UK</span>) are also usable as region subtags for language tags. However, newer stability policies (agreed with ISO) have been implemented to avoid deleting subtags that have been withdrawn in ISO 3166-1&#160;; instead they are kept and aliased to the new preferred subtags, or kept as subtags grouping several countries. Some other region grouping subtags are derived from other standards. Under the newer stability policies, old assigned codes that have been withdrawn from ISO 3166-1 should no longer be reassigned to another country or territory (like it occurred in the past for "CS").</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Current_codes">Current codes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Current codes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Decoding_table">Decoding table</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Decoding table">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The following is a colour-coded decoding table of all ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup></p>
<table class="wikitable" align="center">
<caption>Decoding table of ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes</caption>
<tr style="line-height: 100%;">
<td title="user-assigned" style="background: #5FC; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="partial table-partial"><a href="#AA"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AA</span></a></td>
<td title="unassigned" style="background:#ececec;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AB</span></td>

<td title="United Arab Emirates" style="background: #90FF90; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="active table-active"><a href="#AE"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AE</span></a></td>
<td title="Afghanistan" style="background: #90FF90; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="active table-active"><a href="#AF"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AF</span></a></td>
<td title="Antigua and Barbuda" style="background: #90FF90; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="active table-active"><a href="#AG"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AG</span></a></td>
<td title="unassigned" style="background:#ececec;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AH</span></td>
<td title="Anguilla" style="background: #90FF90; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="active table-active"><a href="#AI"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AI</span></a></td>

<td colspan="2" style="background: #90FF90; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="active table-active"></td>
<td colspan="24"><b><a href="#Officially_assigned_code_elements">Officially assigned</a></b>: assigned to a country, territory, or area of geographical interest</td>

<td colspan="2" style="background: #5FC; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="partial table-partial"></td>
<td colspan="24"><b><a href="#User-assigned_code_elements">User-assigned</a></b>: free for assignment at the disposal of users</td>

<td colspan="24"><b><a href="#Exceptional_reservations">Exceptionally reserved</a></b>: reserved on request for restricted use</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="background:#FA8072; color:black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="table-no"></td>
<td colspan="24"><b><a href="#Indeterminate_reservations">Indeterminately reserved</a></b>: used in coding systems associated with ISO 3166-1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="background: #FED; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="dropped table-dropped"></td>
<td colspan="24"><b><a href="#Transitional_reservations">Transitionally reserved</a></b>: deleted from ISO 3166-1 but reserved transitionally</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="background: #EDF; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;" class="dropped table-dropped"></td>
<td colspan="24"><b><a href="#Deleted_codes">Deleted</a></b>: deleted and free for reassignment</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="background:#ececec;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;"></td>
<td colspan="24"><b>Unassigned</b>: free for assignment by the ISO 3166/MA only</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Officially_assigned_code_elements">Officially assigned code elements</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Officially assigned code elements">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The following is a complete list of the 249 current officially assigned ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes, with the following columns:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Code</b> ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 code</li>
<li><b>Country name</b> English short country name officially used by the ISO 3166 Maintenance Agency (ISO 3166/MA)<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup></li>
<li><b>Year</b> Year when alpha-2 code was first officially assigned (1974, first edition of ISO 3166)</li>
<li><b>ccTLD</b> Corresponding <a href="/wiki/Country_code_top-level_domain" title="Country code top-level domain">country code top-level domain</a> (note that some are inactive); exceptions where another ccTLD is assigned for the country are shown in parentheses</li>
<li><b>ISO 3166-2</b> Corresponding <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-2" title="ISO 3166-2">ISO 3166-2</a> codes</li>
<li><b>Notes</b> Any unofficial notes</li>
</ul>

<th class="unsortable">Notes</th>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="User-assigned_code_elements">User-assigned code elements</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: User-assigned code elements">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><span id="AA"></span><span id="QM"></span><span id="QN"></span><span id="QO"></span><span id="QP"></span><span id="QQ"></span><span id="QR"></span><span id="QS"></span><span id="QT"></span><span id="QU"></span> <span id="QV"></span><span id="QW"></span><span id="QX"></span><span id="QY"></span><span id="QZ"></span><span id="XA"></span><span id="XB"></span><span id="XC"></span><span id="XD"></span><span id="XE"></span> <span id="XF"></span><span id="XG"></span><span id="XH"></span><span id="XI"></span><span id="XJ"></span><span id="XK"></span><span id="XL"></span><span id="XM"></span><span id="XN"></span><span id="XO"></span> <span id="XP"></span><span id="XQ"></span><span id="XR"></span><span id="XS"></span><span id="XT"></span><span id="XU"></span><span id="XV"></span><span id="XW"></span><span id="XX"></span><span id="XY"></span> <span id="XZ"></span><span id="ZZ"></span></p>
<p>User-assigned code elements are codes at the disposal of users who need to add further names of countries, territories, or other geographical entities to their in-house application of ISO 3166-1, and the ISO 3166/MA will never use these codes in the updating process of the standard. The following alpha-2 codes can be user-assigned: <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AA</span>, <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">QM</span> to <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">QZ</span>, <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XA</span> to <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XZ</span>, and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">ZZ</span>. For example:</p>
<ul>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">QZ</span> is being used by the <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">World Intellectual Property Organization</a> as an indicator for the <a href="/wiki/Community_Plant_Variety_Office" title="Community Plant Variety Office">Community Plant Variety Office</a>.</li>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XN</span> is being used by the <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">World Intellectual Property Organization</a> as an indicator for the <a href="/wiki/Nordic_Patent_Institute" title="Nordic Patent Institute">Nordic Patent Institute</a>, an international organization common to Denmark, Iceland, Norway and Sweden.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup></li>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XU</span> is being used by the <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">World Intellectual Property Organization</a> as an indicator for the <a href="/wiki/International_Union_for_the_Protection_of_New_Varieties_of_Plants" title="International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants">International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants</a>.</li>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XV</span> is being used by the <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">World Intellectual Property Organization</a> as an indicator for the <a href="/wiki/Visegrad_Patent_Institute" title="Visegrad Patent Institute">Visegrad Patent Institute</a>.</li>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XX</span> is being used by the <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">World Intellectual Property Organization</a> as an indicator for unknown states, other entities or organizations.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/UN/LOCODE" title="UN/LOCODE">UN/LOCODE</a> assigns <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XZ</span> to represent installations in <a href="/wiki/International_waters" title="International waters">international waters</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-unlocode_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-unlocode-8">[8]</a></sup></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a> <a href="/wiki/Common_Locale_Data_Repository" title="Common Locale Data Repository">Common Locale Data Repository</a> assigns <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">QO</span> to represent Outlying Oceania (a multi-territory region containing <a href="/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">Antarctica</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bouvet_Island" title="Bouvet Island">Bouvet Island</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Cocos_(Keeling)_Islands" title="Cocos (Keeling) Islands">Cocos (Keeling) Islands</a>, <a href="/wiki/Christmas_Island" title="Christmas Island">Christmas Island</a>, <a href="/wiki/South_Georgia_and_the_South_Sandwich_Islands" title="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands">South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heard_Island_and_McDonald_Islands" title="Heard Island and McDonald Islands">Heard Island and McDonald Islands</a>, the <a href="/wiki/British_Indian_Ocean_Territory" title="British Indian Ocean Territory">British Indian Ocean Territory</a>, the <a href="/wiki/French_Southern_Territories" class="mw-redirect" title="French Southern Territories">French Southern Territories</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Minor_Outlying_Islands" title="United States Minor Outlying Islands">United States Minor Outlying Islands</a>), and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">ZZ</span> to represent "Unknown or Invalid Territory". Before the adoption of the macroregion code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EU</span> by ISO, CLDR also used <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">QU</span> to represent the <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">European Union</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup></li>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XK</span> is being used by the <a href="/wiki/European_Commission" title="European Commission">European Commission</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/International_Monetary_Fund" title="International Monetary Fund">IMF</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Society_for_Worldwide_Interbank_Financial_Telecommunication" title="Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication">SWIFT</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> CLDR and other organizations as a temporary country code for <a href="/wiki/Kosovo" title="Kosovo">Kosovo</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup></li>
<li>The code <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XA</span> is being used by <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-ezv.admin.ch_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ezv.admin.ch-24">[24]</a></sup> as a country code for the <a href="/wiki/Canary_Islands" title="Canary Islands">Canary Islands</a>, although <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">IC</span> is already reserved for that purpose.</li>
<li>The codes <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XE</span>, <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XS</span> and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">XW</span> are used by <a href="/wiki/WhatsApp" title="WhatsApp">WhatsApp</a> to represent the flags of England, Scotland and Wales as <a href="/wiki/Emoji" title="Emoji">Emoji</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p><span id="OO"></span> Furthermore, the code element <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">OO</span> is designated as an <a href="/wiki/Escape_code" class="mw-redirect" title="Escape code">escape code</a> if the number of regular user-assigned code elements is not sufficient.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Reserved_code_elements">Reserved code elements</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Reserved code elements">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Reserved code elements are codes which have become obsolete, or are required in order to enable a particular user application of the standard but do not qualify for inclusion in ISO 3166-1. To avoid transitional application problems and to aid users who require specific additional code elements for the functioning of their coding systems, the ISO 3166/MA, when justified, reserves these codes which it undertakes not to use for other than specified purposes during a limited or indeterminate period of time. The reserved alpha-2 codes can be divided into the following four categories: <a href="#Exceptional_reservations">exceptional reservations</a>, <a href="#Transitional_reservations">transitional reservations</a>, <a href="#Indeterminate_reservations">indeterminate reservations</a>, and <a href="#Codes_currently_agreed_not_to_use">codes currently agreed not to use</a>.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Exceptional_reservations">Exceptional reservations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Exceptional reservations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Exceptionally reserved code elements are codes reserved at the request of national ISO member bodies, governments and international organizations, which are required in order to support a particular application, as specified by the requesting body and limited to such use; any further use of such code elements is subject to approval by the ISO 3166/MA. The following alpha-2 codes are currently exceptionally reserved:</p>

<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Transitional_reservations">Transitional reservations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Transitional reservations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Transitional reserved code elements are codes reserved after their deletion from ISO 3166-1. These codes may be used only during a transitional period of at least five years while new code elements that may have replaced them are taken into use. These codes may be reassigned by the ISO 3166/MA after the expiration of the transitional period. The following alpha-2 codes are currently transitionally reserved:</p>

<th><span class="nowrap">ISO 3166-3</span></th>
<th class="unsortable">Notes</th>
</tr>

<p>For each deleted alpha-2 code, an entry for the corresponding former country name is included in <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-3" title="ISO 3166-3">ISO 3166-3</a>. Each entry is assigned a four-letter alphabetic code, where the first two letters are the deleted alpha-2 code.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Indeterminate_reservations">Indeterminate reservations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Indeterminate reservations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Indeterminately reserved code elements are <a href="/wiki/List_of_international_vehicle_registration_codes" title="List of international vehicle registration codes">codes used to designate road vehicles</a> under the 1949 and <a href="/wiki/Vienna_Convention_on_Road_Traffic" title="Vienna Convention on Road Traffic">1968 United Nations Conventions on Road Traffic</a> but differing from those contained in ISO 3166-1. These code elements are expected eventually to be either eliminated or replaced by code elements within ISO 3166-1. In the meantime, the ISO 3166/MA has reserved such code elements for an indeterminate period. Any use beyond the application of the two Conventions is discouraged and will not be approved by the ISO 3166/MA. Moreover, these codes may be reassigned by the ISO 3166/MA at any time. The following alpha-2 codes are currently indeterminately reserved:</p>
<table class="wikitable sortable">

<th>Area name or country name</th>
<th>Notes</th>

<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Codes_currently_agreed_not_to_use">Codes currently agreed not to use</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Codes currently agreed not to use">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In addition, the ISO 3166/MA will not use the following alpha-2 codes at the present stage, as they are used for international <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property_organization" title="Intellectual property organization">intellectual property organizations</a> in <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">WIPO</a> Standard ST.3:</p>
<table class="wikitable sortable">
<tr>
<th>Code</th>
<th>Organization name</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="AP"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">AP</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/African_Regional_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="African Regional Intellectual Property Organization">African Regional Industrial Property Organization</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="BX"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">BX</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Benelux_Office_for_Intellectual_Property" title="Benelux Office for Intellectual Property">Benelux Trademarks and Design Offices</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="EF"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EF</span></td>
<td>Union of Countries under the <a href="/wiki/EU_patent#1970s_and_1980s:_proposed_Community_Patent_Convention" class="mw-redirect" title="EU patent">European Community Patent Convention</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="EM"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EM</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Office_for_Harmonization_in_the_Internal_Market" class="mw-redirect" title="Office for Harmonization in the Internal Market">European Trademark Office</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="EP"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EP</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/European_Patent_Organisation" title="European Patent Organisation">European Patent Organization</a> (Union of countries under the <a href="/wiki/European_Patent_Convention" title="European Patent Convention">European Patent Convention</a>)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="EV"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EV</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Eurasian_Patent_Organization" title="Eurasian Patent Organization">Eurasian Patent Organization</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="GC"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">GC</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/GCC_Patent_Office" title="GCC Patent Office">Patent Office of the Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf (GCC)</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="IB"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">IB</span></td>
<td>International Bureau of <a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">WIPO</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="OA"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">OA</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Organisation_Africaine_de_la_Propri%C3%A9t%C3%A9_Intellectuelle" title="Organisation Africaine de la Proprit Intellectuelle">African Intellectual Property Organization</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td id="WO"><span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">WO</span></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/World_Intellectual_Property_Organization" title="World Intellectual Property Organization">World Intellectual Property Organization</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>WIPO Standard ST.3 actually uses <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EA</span>, instead of <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EV</span>, to represent the <a href="/wiki/Eurasian_Patent_Organization" title="Eurasian Patent Organization">Eurasian Patent Organization</a>. However, <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EA</span> was already <a href="#Exceptional_reservations">exceptionally reserved</a> by the ISO 3166/MA to represent <a href="/wiki/Ceuta" title="Ceuta">Ceuta</a> and <a href="/wiki/Melilla" title="Melilla">Melilla</a> for customs purposes. The ISO 3166/MA proposed in 1995 that <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">EV</span> be used by WIPO to represent the Eurasian Patent Organization; however, this request was not honoured by WIPO.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Deleted_codes">Deleted codes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Deleted codes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Besides the codes currently <a href="#Transitional_reservations">transitionally reserved</a> and two other codes currently <a href="#Exceptional_reservations">exceptionally reserved</a> (<span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">FX</span> for <a href="/wiki/Metropolitan_France" title="Metropolitan France">France, Metropolitan</a> and <span style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">SU</span> for <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">USSR</a>), the following alpha-2 codes have also been deleted from ISO 3166-1:<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[26]</a></sup></p>

<p>For each deleted alpha-2 code, an entry for the corresponding former country name is included in <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-3" title="ISO 3166-3">ISO 3166-3</a>. Each entry is assigned a four-letter alphabetic code, where the first two letters are the deleted alpha-2 code.</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sources_and_external_links">Sources and external links</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=ISO_3166-1_alpha-2&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Sources and external links">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.iso.org/iso/country_codes.htm">ISO 3166 Maintenance Agency</a>, International Organization for Standardization (ISO)

</ul>
</li>

<ul>

</ul>
